{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0331c097-9c92-47ca-abcb-a99a86ed9541","content":"Yes, both are correct and they work together in .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Adjusts the page padding so content avoids the notch/dynamic island. You need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — Lets a specific layout extend *into* the safe area, even when the page respects it. Perfect for full-bleed background images.\n\nTypical pattern:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        <!-- Other content stays within safe area via page padding -->\n        <StackLayout Padding=\"20\" VerticalOptions=\"Center\">\n            <Label Text=\"Hello, iPhone!\" />\n        </StackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe two properties are complementary — the page-level setting protects most content, while `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual layouts lets you opt out where needed. Your tutorial's guidance is sound.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aac41267-1ff3-4607-97de-a802c0b658a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling for iOS has evolved:\n\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` was the original approach using platform-specifics (`Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`).\n\n\n- In more recent versions, particularly .NET 9 and beyond, the approach shifted toward using `Padding` with `SafeAreaInsets` or the `IgnoreSafeArea` property directly on layouts.\n- The `IgnoreSafeArea` property on layouts like Grid allows you to control whether that specific element respects the safe area boundaries, which is useful for full-bleed background images.\n- Both `UseSafeArea` and `IgnoreSafeArea` should remain valid in .NET 10, though I want to verify the exact namespace requirements since there were some changes around .NET 8 or 9 regarding how safe areas are handled.","outputTokens":1089,"requestId":"9815:2CBD0C:172A1A2:19D4524:6A0521C3"},"id":"36c5aab7-0231-4cbd-b19d-bf70b9f29d54","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:14:00.526Z","parentId":"ed77fc8e-dbeb-4bfb-848d-48053cb55e38"}
